    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-06-15T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-06-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="162"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d162">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 639.003/28.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-06-15">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 15, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 53.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department acknowledges the receipt of your
                    dispatch No. 47, of April 26, 1911, relative to the law of the Dominican
                    Republic providing for the imposition of a stamp tax on foreign and domestic
                    letters of exchange, etc., and a resolution of the Dominican Congress approving
                    and putting into operation a municipal surtax upon articles of import levied by
                    the commune of Santo Domingo.</p>
                <p>If you have not already done so, you will reiterate and reaffirm the views of
                    this Government as to the proper interpretation of the convention of February 8,
                    1907, as contained in the Department’s instruction No. 29 of March 1, 1911, and
                    the accompanying data.</p>
                <p>The Department awaits your full report on the workings of the taxes in
                    question.</p>
                <p>I am, etc.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">P. C. Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
